# Qwertystock service notifications and versioned deploys

- Telegram service and product-flow notifications for qwertystock production go only to chat `-1003904421498`, forum topic `Qwerty`.
- OAuth registration/login, non-empty cart open, payment selected, payment rejected, and payment completed events must notify the `Qwerty` topic.
- Messages must be short and in Russian. Avoid noisy status dumps; include only the changed service/state and a compact reason.
- Do not notify on normal RAM percentage drift. Alert only on threshold failure or recovery.
- RAM/swap alerts are critical-only: alert when available RAM is under 5% or swap usage is 95% and above. Do not alert or recover-notify for normal 70-80% swap usage.
- Do not send "deploy started" style production messages. Notify only after the update is applied and the server has switched to the next version.
- Suppress short PM2/systemd restart transients during controlled deploys; alert only if the failure persists beyond the configured grace period.
- Known baseline failures, such as the inherited degraded RAID state observed on 2026-05-18, must not repeat-alert every monitor cycle. Notify only on first discovery, meaningful state change, or recovery.
- Every production deploy must have a version identifier: git SHA or explicit release version. The notification must include that version.
- Production deploys should use versioned release directories and an atomic `current` symlink switch when possible.
- Git commit and push events for the qwertystock main-site repo must notify the `Qwerty` topic with a short Russian message.
- Git notifications must include the project version, starting from `0.0.01`, plus branch and short commit SHA when available.
- Git notification hooks must not store Telegram bot tokens in tracked files. Use environment variables, `.git/qwertystock-notify.env`, or server-side secret files.
- Normal delivery flow: test locally, bump `VERSION`, push `main`, GitHub webhook calls production, production fetches/builds/restarts, then production sends the final deploy notification.
- The production deploy webhook must verify GitHub `X-Hub-Signature-256` and accept only `push` events for `refs/heads/main`.
